[1] Cholera - Tanzania (Zanzibar)
Date: Wed, 29 Mar 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: TODAYonline [edited]
<http://www.todayonline.com/articles/109797print.asp>

At least 4 people have died of cholera in the past week on Tanzania's
Zanzibar archipelago, officials said, announcing the creation of a task
force to fight the disease. In addition to the deaths -- 3 last week on the
island of Pemba and 1 this week on the main island of Unguja -- more than
120 Zanzibaris have been sickened with cholera symptoms, health minister
Sultan Mohamed Mugheiry said.
He said 2 special health facilities had been set up to deal with the
illness, which appears to be spreading, but urged islanders to improve
their hygiene and ensure that water they use for cooking or drinking is clean.
"The most important prevention is for people to observe hygiene," Mugheiry
told reporters at a news conference, warning that he would order the
closure of schools, restaurants and other facilities that do not meet
health standards. He said a preliminary investigation had shown the
outbreak was the result of a lack of proper toilets, including in schools
on Pemba, and the use of contaminated water despite repeated appeals for
water to be boiled.
Cholera has repeatedly hit Zanzibar in recent years, with the last severe
outbreak recorded in 1997 when more than 1100 people were taken ill by the
disease, at least 124 of whom died.
--
