[3] Cholera - Angola (Kwanza-Norte)
Date: Mon, 27 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Angola Press [edited]
<http://www.angolapress-angop.ao/noticia-e.asp?ID=427892>

Eight people have died out of the 26 recorded cases of cholera in the last
7 days in Ndalatando, northern Kwanza-Norte Province, in the sequence of
the disease that has been hitting this region. According to Kwanza Norte`s
provincial hospital director, Caetano Jose Miguel, the 26 cases were
registered in Sambizanga and 11 de Novembro wards, with the dead being
mostly children 9 years old or younger.
Caetano Jose said that the Health Provincial Board, through its disease
control department, is engaged in the evaluation of deaths that occur in
the township, to identify if the deaths are being caused by cholera. The
health provincial administration is appealing to the population to follow
preventive measures to protect themselves from the disease, such as basic
sanitation in the area, cleaning toilets, boiling water or disinfecting the
water before drinking it, among other measures.
******
[4] Cholera - Angola (Benguela, Kwanza-Norte)
Date: Mon, 27 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Prensa Latina [edited]
<http://www.plenglish.com/Article.asp?ID=%7BBF9A8715-4755-4BA0-842C-275B8E4D0EB9%7D&language=EN>

The cholera epidemic seriously affecting Luanda for a month has spread to 2
other provinces with a total of 42 people dead, revealed deputy health
minister Jose Van Dunem on Mon, 27 Mar 2006. Van Dumen confirmed the report
of 12 and 8 deaths in Benguela and north Kwanza respectively, and dozens of
infected people.
The bacterium has attacked the population of Boavista and infected the
zones of Ilhia, Viana, Mutamba, Sambizanga, Cacuaco, Cazenga and Ingombota.
The Health Ministry intensified the sanitation measures to protect the
population from the dangerous disease, transmitted through water, polluted
food and direct contact with infected people.
