[5] Cholera - Angola (Luanda)
Date: Sun, 26 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and Angola Press Agency (Luanda) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200603270006.html>

One person died out of 84 cases of cholera recorded in the last 24 hours,
in Luanda, [since the beginning] of the epidemic outbreak that hit the
country's capital beginning 13 Feb 2006.
The provincial health director Vita Vemba said the cases were registered in
the municipalities of Sambizanga (48), Ingombotas (20), Cazenga (10),
Maianga (3), Rangel (2), Kilamba Kiaxi (2) and Samba (1). The death
occurred in Cazenga.
A total of 23 people have so far died since the start of the outbreak, out
of 815 cases. No cases had been recorded in Viana and Cacuaco districts in
the last 24 hours.
******
[6] Cholera - Angola (Luanda)
Date: Tue, 28 Mar 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Angola Press [edited]
<http://www.angolapress-angop.ao/noticia-e.asp?ID=428366>

90 new cases of cholera, without any deaths, were registered in the last 24
hours, in Luanda, adding to 1038, since 13 Feb 2006, date of the disease
outbreak in the province.
The information was given by the Health Luanda provincial director, Vita
Vemba, stating that the illness already caused 23 deaths, representing a
mortality rate of 2 per cent.
About the spread of the disease in every municipality, Vita Vemba said that
it is due to basic sanitation problems, lack of toilets in some areas, and
low water quality, aggravated by the lack of water distribution network in
most parts of the city.
******
[7] Cholera - Uganda (Moyo)
Date: Sat, 25 Mar 2006
From: Alfonso J. Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: AllAfrica.com and New Vision (Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200603270026.html>

Moyo district has been hit by the less common cholera subtype Inaba, the
commissioner for community health, Dr Sam Okware, has said. He said Inaba
has killed 3 people in the district.
Okware said on Thu, 23 Mar 2006, "There is a big problem in Sudan. This
rare subtype could have been imported from there because there is already a
severe cholera epidemic."
Earlier reports indicated that a cholera-like disease had hit the district
with over 20 people admitted to Obongi health center in critical condition.
At least 5 people were being admitted every day with mild diarrhea.
However, Okware said samples tested from Kampala showed Inaba, a milder
type compared to the typical cholera. "With Inaba, the diarrhea is not as
intensive as in the common cholera. It (diarrhea) is mild and patients tend
to improve faster, hence not a serious danger," Okware said.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The flagellar (H) antigens of _V. cholerae_ are shared with many water
vibrios and therefore are of no use in distinguishing strains causing
epidemic cholera. The O (somatic) antigens, however, do distinguish strains
of _V. cholerae_ into 139 known serotypes. Almost all of these strains of
_V. cholerae_ are nonvirulent. Until the emergence of the Bengal strain
(which is "non-O1"), a single serotype, designated O1, has been responsible
for epidemic cholera.
However, there are 3 distinct O1 biotypes, named Ogawa, Inaba, and
Hikojima, each of which may display the "classical" or El Tor phenotype.
The Bengal strain (O139) is a new serological strain with a unique O
antigen, which partly explains the lack of residual immunity.
A map showing the Moyo district in Uganda is available at:
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moyo> - Mod.LL]
